Objective
Understand why Docker was introduced, what an Image and Container are, and learn the basic Docker commands.
________________________________________
1. Why was Docker introduced?
Before Docker
Developers often faced this problem:
"It works on my machine."
But when the same application was deployed to another server, it failed because:
•	Different operating system
•	Different Java/Python/Node.js version
•	Missing libraries
•	Different environment configuration
This created deployment issues.
________________________________________
Docker Solution
Docker packages:
•	Application
•	Runtime
•	Libraries
•	Dependencies
•	Configuration
into one package called an Image.
That same image can run consistently on different machines.
________________________________________
2. Image
Definition
An Image is a blueprint/template used to create containers.
It contains everything required to run an application.
Think of it as:
•	Cake recipe
•	House blueprint
•	Mobile phone design
One image can create many containers.
Example:
Ubuntu Image
        │
        ├── Container 1
        ├── Container 2
        └── Container 3
________________________________________
3. Container
Definition
A Container is a running instance of an image.
Containers are isolated from each other.
Each container has:
•	Its own filesystem
•	Its own processes
•	Its own environment
Containers are temporary (ephemeral) by design.
Deleting a container deletes everything inside it unless data is stored outside the container (for example, in a Docker volume).
________________________________________
4. Image vs Container
Image	Container
Blueprint	Running instance
Read-only template	Running environment
Can create many containers	Created from one image
Stays on disk	Can be started, stopped, or removed
________________________________________
5. Docker Lifecycle
Image
   │
docker run
   ▼
Running Container
   │
docker stop
   ▼
Stopped Container
   │
docker start
   ▼
Running Again
   │
docker rm
   ▼
Container Deleted
________________________________________
6. Commands Learned
docker run
Creates and starts a new container.
Example:
docker run hello-world
Example:
docker run -it ubuntu bash
Meaning:
•	docker → Docker CLI
•	run → Create and start a container
•	-i → Interactive mode
•	-t → Allocate a terminal
•	ubuntu → Image name
•	bash → Start Bash shell
________________________________________
docker images
Shows all images stored locally.
Example:
docker images
________________________________________
docker ps
Shows only running containers.
Example:
docker ps
________________________________________
docker ps -a
Shows all containers.
Includes:
•	Running containers
•	Stopped containers
Example:
docker ps -a


